Content: The author wrote this article most likely to —

A.Choice: share the history of the International Space Station

Key.Rationale: The history of the space station is not given.

B.Choice: persuade people to learn about the International Space Station

Key.Rationale: The author is not trying to persuade the reader.

C.Choice: provide information about a new tool used on the International Space Station

Key.Rationale: The author's main purpose is to provide information.

D.Choice: describe some of the dangers on the International Space Station

Key.Rationale: The author does not describe dangers on the space station.

Content: The details in paragraph 5 support the main idea that R2's design —

F.Choice: helps it accomplish certain kinds of tasks

Key.Rationale: The details in paragraph 5 describe how R2's design helps it accomplish tasks.

G.Choice: took years for scientists to plan

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 5 does not give details about how long the scientists planned.

H.Choice: causes it to be too heavy to complete certain tasks

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 5 does not indicate that its weight makes it too heavy to complete tasks.

J.Choice: works better in space than in a factory

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 5 does not give details about the robot working in a factory.

Content: Read this quotation from paragraph 9 of the article.
:box:John Olson, a director at NASA headquarters in Washington, D.C., says that the project “will allow us to go farther and achieve more than we can probably even imagine today.”
Which detail from the article supports this idea?

A.Choice: Since its hands are shaped like human hands, R2 can use human tools to complete tasks traditionally performed by astronauts.

Key.Rationale: This detail only focuses on what R2 can do now.

B.Choice: Astronauts will also appreciate the fact that the robot can perform its duties without constant supervision.

Key.Rationale: This detail shows only that R2 does not need constant supervision.

C.Choice: In the future humanoid robots will be astronauts' eyes in space, going places considered too difficult or unsafe for astronauts to explore.

Key.Rationale: This detail shows how R2 will allow us to go farther and achieve more.

D.Choice: They will grasp and hold onto handrails as the robot moves through the space station.

Key.Rationale: This detail does not support the idea.

Content: Which text feature provides information about R2's abilities?

Key.Rationale: The subheadings do not give information about R2's abilities.
The title does not give information about R2's abilities.

H.Choice: The caption of the first photograph

Key.Rationale: The caption identifies only the robot.

J.Choice: The caption of the second photograph

Key.Rationale: The caption indicates R2 has the ability to operate a task board.

Content: What is the best summary of paragraphs 4 through 6?

A.Choice: R2 is a new humanoid robot that will help astronauts on the space station. Its arms can hold 20 pounds, and its fingers apply 5 pounds of force to pick things up.

Key.Rationale: This summary is too partial.

B.Choice: Scientists have built a special humanoid robot called R2 that looks and moves like a human. GM and NASA worked together to create a robot that could complete simple jobs.

Key.Rationale: The summary focuses on only a portion of the section.

C.Choice: Scientists at NASA and GM have developed a humanoid robot called R2 for space missions. R2's body has features that help it move like a human and complete tasks independently.

Key.Rationale: The summary gives important information from each paragraph.

D.Choice: R2 is a humanoid robot built to help astronauts on the space station. It weighs 330 pounds and cost $2.5 million to build, but astronauts like the fact that it will give them more time to rest.

Key.Rationale: The summary includes information not in the selection.

Content: What is the most likely reason the author included the information in paragraph 10?

F.Choice: To explain what robots of the future will be required to do

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 10 does not explain any requirements.

G.Choice: To highlight the effectiveness of using humanoid robots in space

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 10 is not about the effectiveness of robots in space.

H.Choice: To support the idea that businesses should work together on inventions

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 10 is not about businesses working together.

J.Choice: To describe the next stage for the humanoid robot

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 10 describes the next steps of developing legs for R2.

Content: According to the article, the annual event began when  —

A.Choice: a local family wanted to prove they could win an award

Key.Rationale: The event did not start as a competition.

B.Choice: neighbors gathered at a local fruit farm

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 1 says the event began as a neighborhood get-together.

C.Choice: a frost ruined a crop of cherries at a local fruit farm

Key.Rationale: The only mention of a frost affecting cherries was during last year's crop.

D.Choice: people came to the town to seek employment

Key.Rationale: This information is not in the passage.

Content: Look at the dictionary entry.

:box:shot \'shät\ noun
1. a throw in an effort to score points in a game
2. a small amount applied at once
3. a try or attempt
4. an effective remark
Which definition best matches the way the word s͟h͟o͟t is used in paragraph 8?

Key.Rationale: Krause is not scoring points in a game.
Krause is not applying an amount.
Krause is attempting another try at the title.
Krause is not making a remark.

Content: Which sentence best states the main idea of the article?

A.Choice: A truck driver from Chicago was the champion of the pit spit in Eau Claire in 2012.

Key.Rationale: This sentence is only one detail in the article.

B.Choice: The pit spit, which features many eager participants, will be taking place again at the Tree-Mendus Fruit Farm in Eau Claire.

Key.Rationale: This sentence includes the necessary information about the event.

C.Choice: Although last year's cold weather kept the cherry harvest small, this year the harvest will be ideal for the pit spit.

Key.Rationale: This sentence is only about the harvest.

D.Choice: Many members of the Krause family will be participating again this year at the pit spit.

Key.Rationale: This sentence is only about the Krause family.

Content: Based on the information in the article, what can the reader infer about the contest?

F.Choice: Some people travel from places outside the city to participate in the event.

Key.Rationale: The article mentions contestants from Chicago, Arizona, and California participating.

G.Choice: The contestants are required to grow the cherries that are used in the event.

Key.Rationale: The article mentions only cherries from one fruit farm.

H.Choice: The contestants need to have participated in a similar event in the past.

Key.Rationale: There is no information in the article indicating requirements for contestants.

J.Choice: People from the town enjoyed the event only when it was a small neighborhood gathering.

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence to suggest people don't enjoy the event.

Content: The reader can tell that the speaker is experienced at spitting cherry pits because she  —

A.Choice: provides several suggestions about the best way to prepare for the activity

Key.Rationale: The speaker gives advice on how to spit the cherry pit.

B.Choice: identifies the number of times she has practiced over the summer

Key.Rationale: The speaker does not indicate practicing.

C.Choice: reveals that there is a bowl of cherries in her kitchen

Key.Rationale: The speaker is offering advice about where to find cherries.

D.Choice: states that she has spit a pit in her yard

Key.Rationale: The speaker does not spit the pit in the yard.

Content: What is one important effect of the rhyme scheme of the poem?

F.Choice: It focuses the reader on the most important words in the poem.

Key.Rationale: The rhyming words are not the most important words.

G.Choice: It helps the reader visualize the problem the speaker experiences.

Key.Rationale: The rhyming words do not help the reader visualize a problem.

H.Choice: It creates a rhythm that emphasizes the quick actions in the poem.

Key.Rationale: The many rhyming words shorten the rhythm and imitate the quick actions of spitting a cherry pit.

J.Choice: It helps explain what spitting a cherry pit sounds like.

Key.Rationale: The rhyming words do not explain the sound of spitting a cherry pit.

Content: Which line from the poem best helps the reader understand the meaning of l͟a͟u͟n͟c͟h?

Key.Rationale: The line is a step in preparing for the launch of the pit.
The line indicates there will be advice about how to spit the cherry pit.
The line is a step in the process of spitting the cherry pit.
The line indicates that aiming toward the fence is the way to launch the pit.

Content: What is most likely the reason the poet compares spitting cherry pits to playing baseball?

F.Choice: To show that spitting cherry pits is just as much a team sport as baseball

Key.Rationale: Spitting cherries is not a team sport.

G.Choice: To help the reader relate a well-known activity to an activity that might be unfamiliar

Key.Rationale: Comparing the activity to baseball helps the reader imagine the activity better.

H.Choice: To explain that less time is required for spitting cherry pits than for playing baseball

Key.Rationale: There is no indication about how much time either of the activities takes.

J.Choice: To show the reader that some activities are more interesting than others

Key.Rationale: The speaker does not take a position on how interesting the activity is.

Content: Which message is expressed by both the article and the poem?

A.Choice: Some activities can be appreciated simply for the fun of them.

Key.Rationale: The town celebrates the contest with fun activities, and the speaker is describing a “summerfun” activity.

B.Choice: Even if you do not succeed right away, you must keep on trying.

Key.Rationale: There is no indication that you must keep trying in either selection.

C.Choice: A great talent is often shared by family members.

Key.Rationale: A family member does not participate in spitting cherry pits in the poem.

D.Choice: It is important to be a polite and kindhearted winner.

Key.Rationale: Neither selection focuses on polite or kindhearted winners.

Content: What is one main difference between the event the author describes in the article and the event the speaker describes in the poem?

F.Choice: The type of cherry pit that is used

Key.Rationale: There is no indication of what type of cherry pit is used in either selection.
The setting for one is a fruit tree farm and the setting for the other is a back yard.
The excitement people feel is not discussed.
The rules are not discussed in the article or the poem.

Content: Which of the following describes a difference between the article and the poem?

A.Choice: The article provides details of an event related to spitting cherry pits, while the poem describes the process of spitting cherry pits.

Key.Rationale: The article is detailing an event, and the poem is describing a process.

B.Choice: The article provides information about activities that occur before a contest, while the poem describes the results of a contest.

Key.Rationale: The poem does not describe the results of a contest.

C.Choice: The article focuses mainly on the people who spit cherry pits, while the poem features those who observe the activity.

Key.Rationale: No one is observing the activity in the poem.

D.Choice: The article explains how to organize a local competition, while the poem highlights how to get involved in one.

Key.Rationale: The article does not explain organizing a competition and the poem does not involve a competition.

Content: Which idea is expressed in both the article and the poem?

F.Choice: Spitting cherry pits is a difficult activity to plan and organize.

Key.Rationale: Neither selection focuses on the difficulty of planning and organizing an activity.

G.Choice: Spitting a cherry pit as far as possible can be fun.

Key.Rationale: Both selections indicate that the activity is fun.

H.Choice: The process of spitting a cherry pit is exciting to describe.

Key.Rationale: The article does not describe the process of spitting a cherry pit.

J.Choice: Recording the distance a cherry pit traveled is difficult.

Key.Rationale: The article does not indicate any difficulty in recording distance, and the poem does not record distance.

Content: Which sentence from the selection best shows that Catchings cares about other people?

A.Choice: Catchings always sat up front and stayed after class to ask questions about the lessons.

Key.Rationale: The sentence shows that she cares about doing well in school.

B.Choice: During her four years at the university, the Lady Vols had an overall record of 134 wins and only 10 losses, partly because of Catchings's outstanding play.

Key.Rationale: The sentence focuses on her college basketball team's record.

C.Choice: Most importantly, she combines her love for basketball with her passion for helping children achieve their dreams.

Key.Rationale: The sentence shows that she cares about helping children.

D.Choice: She stronglybelieves — and is living proof — that working hard and having confidence can help anyone succeed.

Key.Rationale: The sentence focuses on her belief in hard work and confidence.

Content: Read the following information.
:box:Sur-: Anglo-French prefix meaning “above”
This information helps the reader understand that the word s͟u͟r͟p͟a͟s͟s͟e͟d in paragraph 2 means  —

Key.Rationale: She passed above or did better than her schoolmates.
It is comparing her abilities to her school mates and speaking kindly doesn't make sense.
There is no indication of how much time she spent with other schoolmates.
There is no discussion of how her schoolmates felt about her.

Content: What event in Catchings's life has most influenced her charity work?

A.Choice: She participated on the U.S. Women's Olympi Basketball Team.

Key.Rationale: The event was an achievement, but it did not influence her charity work.
The event took place long before she became involved with charity work.

C.Choice: She decided to stop hiding her disability while in college.

Key.Rationale: After speaking about her disability, she became an inspiration to others.

D.Choice: She led her high school teams to state championships.

Key.Rationale: She began her charity work long after high school.

Content: Catchings's actions throughout her school years suggest that she —

F.Choice: wanted to be noticed by her classmates and teammates

Key.Rationale: She kept her hearing loss a secret to fit in with her classmates.

G.Choice: was determined to do her best in many areas of her life

Key.Rationale: She worked hard to overcome her disadvantage, which led to surpassing her classmates and teammates.

H.Choice: thought her hearing would improve as she got older

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that she thought her hearing would improve.

J.Choice: knew she would play professional basketball one day

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that she knew she would play professional basketball.

Content: What is a theme in the selection?

Key.Rationale: There is no support for everyone having a unique talent.

B.Choice: People make difficult decisions every day.

Key.Rationale: Making difficult decisions is not the focus of this selection.

C.Choice: Young people need community support in order to succeed.

Key.Rationale: Community support of young people is not the focus of this selection.

D.Choice: People can often overcome obstacles through hard work.

Key.Rationale: The selection showed how Catchings overcame a disability through hard work.

Content: The author organized the selection with subheadings most likely to  —

F.Choice: show how Catchings's actions have affected others

Key.Rationale: The subheadings don't focus on affecting others.

G.Choice: provide information about each person who helped Catchings

Key.Rationale: The subheadings don't give any information about who helped Catchings.

H.Choice: focus on different phases of Catchings's life

Key.Rationale: Each subheading focuses on a different stage of Catchings's life.

J.Choice: highlight the charities that Catchings is most involved with

Key.Rationale: Only one subheading highlights Catchings's charitable work.

Content: What was an unexpected result of Catchings's relationship with Pat Summitt?

A.Choice: Catchings taught Summitt lessons on how to communicate better.

Key.Rationale: There is no indication that Catchings taught Summitt anything about communicating.

B.Choice: Catchings helped Summitt become a better basketball coach.

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that Catchings improved Summitt as a coach.

C.Choice: Summitt taught Catchings how to overcome her disability.

Key.Rationale: Catchings was very successful and had already overcome her disability before playing in college.

D.Choice: Summitt encouraged Catchings to use her disability to set a good example.

Key.Rationale: Summitt was the one who encouraged Catchings to wear hearing aids and be a role model.

Content: Read this sentence from paragraph 12.
:box:I followed, keeping my distance so as not to scare the calf.
What can the reader conclude about the dog from this sentence?

F.Choice: He is no longer interested in getting on the boat with Lewis.

Key.Rationale: The dog does get in the boat while the calf watches.

G.Choice: He is not certain of where Lewis wants to explore next.

Key.Rationale: Where Lewis wants to explore next is not addressed.

H.Choice: He has a new understanding of the calf's feelings.

Key.Rationale: In paragraph 9 the dog realizes the calf is afraid of him, so he keeps his distance.

J.Choice: He is no longer frightened by the calf.

Key.Rationale: The dog was never frightened by the calf.

Content: Which idea is developed throughout the story?

A.Choice: The dog's shock at Lewis's actions

Key.Rationale: The dog is only shocked by Lewis's actions in paragraph 7.

B.Choice: The dog's belief that he is much smarter than the calf

Key.Rationale: The dog mentions being smarter than the calf only once, in paragraph 1.

C.Choice: The dog's concern that he and Lewis have explored the same area

Key.Rationale: There is no indication that the dog and Lewis have explored the area before.

D.Choice: The dog's determination to prevent anything from coming between him and Lewis

Key.Rationale: The dog tries to scare the calf away throughout most of the story and then admits his jealousy at the end.

Content: What do the dog's questions in paragraphs 4, 7, and 10 suggest?

F.Choice: The dog is trying to make sense of the situation.

Key.Rationale: The questions show first the dog's confusion and then the realization that he had misunderstood the situation.

G.Choice: The dog is not familiar with the surroundings.

Key.Rationale: None of the questions concern the dog's surroundings.

H.Choice: The dog is unsure about his feelings for Lewis.

Key.Rationale: It is clear throughout the story that the dog is very attached to Lewis.

J.Choice: The dog is not paying attention to Lewis.

Key.Rationale: The dog is focused on Lewis and the calf.

Content: What is the best summary of paragraphs 1 through 5?

A.Choice: Lewis and the dog enjoy walking together, and on this day, they are traveling near the banks of a river. A buffalo calf ignores the dog and follows Lewis.

Key.Rationale: The calf doesn't ignore the dog; the calf is frightened of the dog.

B.Choice: The dog is taking his usual walk with Lewis when they meet a buffalo calf. The dog thinks the calf is behaving strangely around Lewis.

Key.Rationale: It focuses on only one detail of what happens in the story.

C.Choice: While Lewis and the dog are on a walk, a buffalo calf joins them. Because the calf follows Lewis closely, the dog thinks of a plan to scare it away.

Key.Rationale: It includes what happens at the beginning, middle, and end of the story.

D.Choice: The dog notices that a buffalo calf is following Lewis. The dog decides that he had better stay close to Lewis instead of exploring the area.

Key.Rationale: It focuses on only what happens in paragraph 3.

Content: In paragraph 14, the dog wants to explain —

F.Choice: why he reacted to the calf as he did

Key.Rationale: The dog realizes he was jealous and explains how dogs behave when they are jealous.

G.Choice: that he is still as playful as he used to be

Key.Rationale: The dog doesn't comment on how playful he is.

H.Choice: how he has changed as he has gotten older

Key.Rationale: The dog does not mention changing as he has gotten older.

J.Choice: that young dogs are more lovable than calves

Key.Rationale: The dog doesn't discuss whether puppies are more lovable than calves.

Content: In paragraph 9, the author uses a simile to help the reader understand that the dog suddenly  —

A.Choice: forgives Lewis for paying attention to the calf

Key.Rationale: There is no indication that the dog needs to forgive Lewis.

B.Choice: realizes why the calf is following Lewis

Key.Rationale: What became clear like a mountain stream was that the calf was afraid of the dog.

C.Choice: notices a new place to explore on his walk with Lewis

Key.Rationale: The dog does not notice a new place in this paragraph.

D.Choice: remembers that he and Lewis need to return to the boat

Key.Rationale: There is no indication that the dog remembers to return to the boat.

Content: Which sentence best reveals the dog's view of his relationship with Lewis?

F.Choice: I stayed with Lewis and the calf, but I walked a few yards behind.

Key.Rationale: The sentence doesn't reveal how the dog views their relationship.

G.Choice: I was sure Lewis didn't want him around anymore than I did.

Key.Rationale: The dog's incorrect interpretation doesn't reveal his view of their relationship.

H.Choice: Lewis and I were a team; moving close to Lewis was like moving close to me.

Key.Rationale: The dog sees himself and Lewis as a team that is tied closely together.

J.Choice: Next, Lewis did something that surprised me.

Key.Rationale: The dog's surprise does not reveal how he views the relationship.

Content: The reader can conclude that when Hillerich first asked his father to make wood bats, Hillerich's father  —

A.Choice: planned to change his business by making only wood bats

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 3 says Hillerich's father refused to make bats.

B.Choice: believed metal bats would sell better than wood bats

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that metal bats were in competition with wood bats.

C.Choice: wanted to sell his company rather than make wood bats

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 3 says Hillerich's father wanted to make other products.

D.Choice: thought his company would not benefit from making wood bats

Key.Rationale: Hillerich's father preferred to make other products until his son convinced him bats would be good for business.

Content: In paragraph 6, the details about Ted Williams's experience with Louisville Slugger bats support the idea that  —

F.Choice: professional athletes can notice slight differences in equipment

Key.Rationale: Williams noticed a difference of 5/1000 of an inch.

G.Choice: Louisville Sluggers are not the best bats available to professional baseball players

Key.Rationale: There is no discussion of what is the best bat, only what is the most favored.

H.Choice: negative comments about a product can harm a company's business

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that the company's business was harmed by negative comments.

J.Choice: Louisville Sluggers are better designed today than when they were first made

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that the design is better today, only that bats have changed.

Content: Which sentence best states the main idea of the section title “Old and New”?

A.Choice: They were made with any kind of wood that was available.

Key.Rationale: The sentence is only a detail about old bats.

B.Choice: The shape of today's baseball bats is also more regular — narrow at the handle and wide at the end.

Key.Rationale: It is only a detail about today's bats.

C.Choice: Bats come in different lengths and weights.

Key.Rationale: The sentence is just an observation about bats.

D.Choice: Baseball bats have changed a great deal over the years.

Key.Rationale: The sentence reflects the general idea about the bat's development over time.

Content: What is the meaning of a͟c͟c͟u͟s͟t͟o͟m͟e͟d in paragraph 7?

Key.Rationale: The equipment does not manage the player.
The players have not become different by using the same equipment in games and practices.
The players haven't changed by using the same equipment.
The players are in the habit of using the same equipment.

Content: The reader can infer that one of the main reasons the production of Louisville Sluggers began was because of Hillerich's  —

A.Choice: willingness to use his knowledge of woodworking to help someone

Key.Rationale: Hillerich's offer to make a bat for a player started the business of making bats.

B.Choice: understanding of the game of baseball

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence that Hillerich's understanding of the game started the production of bats.

C.Choice: ability to promote a product using a variety of advertising

Key.Rationale: There is no mention of advertising the bats.

D.Choice: experience playing baseball with a metal bat

Key.Rationale: There is no mention that Hillerich played baseball with any sort of bat.

Content: Based on information in the selection, what is one similarity between Pete Browning and Honus Wagner?

F.Choice: Their success encouraged other players to use Louisville Sluggers.

Key.Rationale: The success of Browning and Wagner with the bats encouraged other players to use the bats.

G.Choice: They both ordered a wood bat that was not made correctly.

Key.Rationale: There is no mention of either of these men getting a bat that was incorrectly made.

H.Choice: Their friendship with Hillerich helped improve their batting skills.

Key.Rationale: There is no mention of either man having a friendship with Hillerich.

J.Choice: They both persuaded Hillerich's father to make Louisville Sluggers.

Key.Rationale: The selection says that Hillerich persuaded his father, not either of these men.
